article.headline: Korver hits six 3-pointers on way to 25 points
article.linkText: Korver's outside shooting lifts No. 19 Creighton
article.story: LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Just when Nebraska looked as if it would make a run at Creighton (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 Associated Press) on Saturday night, Kyle Korver put the kibosh on the Cornhuskers. Korver made six 3-pointers and finished with 25 points to lead the Bluejays to an 81-73 victory. Three of his 3-pointers came in the opening eight minutes as the Bluejays took a 26-9 lead. Nebraska closed to seven points twice in the second half, but each time Korver killed the Huskers' momentum by making a 3. ''That was probably the game,'' Creighton coach Dana Altman said, ''because it saved us from the crowd getting into it.'' Creighton is off to a 9-0 start for the second time in four years and the seventh time in the 85-year history of the program. The Bluejays have won four consecutive games in the series between the state's only Division I basketball programs. It was the Bluejays' second consecutive victory in the Devaney Center, but only the second in the last 14 games in Lincoln. ''It's the other D-I program in the state, so any time you play them, you're going to want to go in and get a victory,'' said Creighton's Tyler McKinney, who had 10 points and 12 assists. ''They may not say it's a rivalry, but it is to us. There's a lot of emotion in a game like this.'' Creighton made 10 of its first 14 shots, including going 6-for-8 from 3-point range, in taking the early lead. The Huskers (4-4) closed to 32-23, but they made only two field goals over the last 7:21 of the half and shot just 30.6 percent in the opening 20 minutes and 37.7 percent for the game. Bowden drilled a 3-pointer and Joe Dabbert converted a three-point play as the Bluejays led 46-35 at halftime. ''We gave them too many open looks to start the game,'' said Nebraska forward Andrew Drevo, who had 23 points and 13 rebounds. ''You can't do that with a team like this and expect to recover.'' The Bluejays launched 28 of their 56 field goal attempts from behind the 3-point arc, making 10. With McKinney and fellow guard DeAnthony Bowden, who had 11 points, threats to penetrate, the 3s were there for the taking for Creighton. ''I liked our aggressiveness offensively,'' Altman said. ''We hit some shots. Our guys took it to the basket. And we hit those 3s, which always helps.'' Nebraska cut Creighton's lead to 54-48 and 57-50, but Korver hit 3-pointers to stem the Huskers' momentum. ''I was feeling it for a couple minutes, I guess, and then I missed a couple after that and got kind of greedy,'' Korver said. Korver was 6-for-14 on 3s and 7-for-17 overall. ''Seven-for-17 is a pretty good effort defensively,'' Huskers coach Barry Collier said, ''but when six of the makes are behind the 3-point line, you can score some points in a hurry. He really hurt us.''
